# Appendix A — Common errors and what they mean

Every SLAT error tells you three things.

1. **What went wrong.** Named. Specific. Not \"syntax error at line 42.\"
2. **Where it went wrong.** File, line, column. Every error carries a
   source position.
3. **What you probably meant.** A did-you-mean hint when there's a
   plausible guess.

This appendix is the catalog. If you see an error in the wild, look
it up here. Every entry has an example.

## `unexpected-end-of-input`

```
slat error: unexpected-end-of-input
  at line 3, column 45
  in file \"example.slat\"

  reader was looking for: )
  did you mean: close the parenthesis at line 1, column 1?
```

You forgot to close a parenthesis. Every `(` needs a matching `)`.

**Fix:** count your parens. The reader tells you the line the
unclosed one started on. Go add the `)`.

## `unmatched-close-paren`

```
slat error: unmatched-close-paren
  at line 2, column 30
  in file \"example.slat\"

  found: )
  reader had no open ( to match
```

You have one extra `)`. Remove it.

## `bad-string-escape`

```
slat error: bad-string-escape
  at line 4, column 12
  in file \"example.slat\"

  found: \\x
  the reader knows only: \\n \\t \\r \\\\ \\\"
```

You used `\\x`, `\\u`, `\\0`, or some other escape that SLAT doesn't
recognize. Only five escapes exist: `\\n \\t \\r \\\\ \\\"`. If you want a
Unicode character, type it literally as UTF-8.

## `unterminated-string`

```
slat error: unterminated-string
  at line 3
  in file \"example.slat\"

  string started at line 3, column 10
  reader reached end of line without seeing the closing \"
```

A string that started on one line and didn't close before a newline —
in `.slatl` framing. Strings can't cross lines in line-delimited mode.

**Fix:** put the closing `\"` on the same line, or switch to `.slat`
framing.

## `bad-number`

```
slat error: bad-number
  at line 5, column 4
  in file \"example.slat\"

  found: 3.14.15
  a number can only have one decimal point
```

The reader tried to parse something as a number and failed. Multiple
decimal points, invalid exponent, missing digits, etc.

## `reserved-keyword`

```
slat error: reserved-keyword
  at line 6, column 15
  in file \"example.slat\"

  found: :_signature
  keywords starting with :_ are reserved for the reader
```

You tried to use a reserved keyword. `:_form`, `:_positional`,
`:_comment`, `:_meta`, `:_bad-line`, `:_tainted` are all reserved.

**Fix:** rename to something without the leading underscore. If you're
trying to smuggle a signature into a record — sign the whole record
instead (Chapter 10).

## `max-depth-exceeded`

```
slat error: max-depth-exceeded
  at line 42, column 128
  in file \"example.slat\"

  depth reached: 129
  max allowed: 128
```

A slat nested more than 128 levels deep. Almost certainly a bug or an
attack.

**Fix:** flatten your structure, or bump the bound with
`:max-depth 256`.

## `max-length-exceeded`

```
slat error: max-length-exceeded
  in file \"example.slat\"

  form-length: 5242881 bytes
  max allowed: 4194304 bytes
```

A single record exceeded 4 MiB. That's larger than any legitimate
mailbox message.

**Fix:** split the record, or bump the bound.

## `slat-bomb-detected`

```
slat error: slat-bomb-detected
  in file \"example.slat\"

  expansion ratio: 12.5×
  max allowed: 10×
```

Structural sharing (`#0=…#0#`) tried to expand a small source into a
large in-memory tree. The reader stopped it.

**Fix:** don't use structural sharing for signed records (canonical
form expands anyway, per Chapter 8 rule 11).

## `fuel-exhausted`

```
slat error: fuel-exhausted
  in file \"example.slat\"

  tokens read: 10000001
  max allowed: 10000000
```

The reader ran through more than 10 million tokens. That's a very
large file.

**Fix:** stream with `.slatl` framing instead of reading whole
documents.

## `type-mismatch`

```
slat error: type-mismatch (from slat-check)
  in record: (event :ts \"not a number\" :kind \"card.opened\")

  field: :ts
  expected: integer
  actual: string
```

You called `slat-check` on a record and one field didn't match its
registered type. Fix the value or fix the registration.

## `signature-verification-failed`

```
slat error: signature-verification-failed

  cid mismatch: computed abc123..., stored def456...
  the signed body has been altered since signing
```

The record's canonical hash doesn't match the CID stored in the
signature envelope. Someone changed the body after it was signed.

**Do not trust this record.** Log it. Drop it.

## `capability-expired`

```
slat error: capability-expired

  not-after: 2026-07-18T00:00:00Z
  now:       2026-07-25T15:00:00Z
```

A capability token has expired. Reject the operation and ask for a
fresh capability.

## `_bad-line` sentinel (tolerant mode)

Not an error thrown — a value returned:

```
(_bad-line
  :input \"(event :ts 1 :kind ...corrupted...\"
  :error \"unexpected end of input at column 30\")
```

In tolerant mode, the reader returns a `_bad-line` record instead of
throwing. Consumers can log it, drop it, or attempt recovery.

## How to read a source position

Every error has a source position: file, line, column. Line numbers
are 1-based. Column numbers are 1-based, in characters (not bytes) of
the input.

Some errors have TWO positions — where the reader was looking, and
where the enclosing form started. Use the enclosing position to find
the un-closed paren or the too-deep nesting.

## Cross-links

- [[book-of-slat-ch07]] — reading and writing, which introduces
  strict and tolerant modes.
- [[book-of-systems]] Chapter 2 — Read the log, which uses `_bad-line`
  extensively.

